    "photo": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/ae/Aristotle_Altemps_Inv8575.jpg",
    "body": "Aristotle (384–322 BCE) was a Greek philosopher and scientist born in Stagira in northern Greece, student of [[Plato]], tutor of Alexander the Great, and founder of the Lyceum. Of all the figures in Western philosophy, only [[Plato]] rivals his influence.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nAristotle's father, Nicomachus, served as court physician to the Macedonian king Amyntas III. After his father's death, Aristotle travelled to Athens at around the age of seventeen to join [[Plato]]'s Academy, where he spent the next two decades — first as a student, then as a fellow researcher. When [[Plato]] died in 348 or 347 BCE, Aristotle left Athens — probably in part because anti-Macedonian sentiment made his position uncomfortable — and settled in Assos on the coast of Asia Minor, where a fellow Academic, Hermias, ruled. He married Pythias, the niece of Hermias. When the Persians lured Hermias into a trap and had him killed, Aristotle moved to the island of Lesbos, conducting zoological research alongside Theophrastus. Philip II of Macedon called him to court in 343 to take charge of his son's education — the boy who would become Alexander the Great was around thirteen at the time.\n\nIn 335 Aristotle returned to Athens and founded his own school in a public exercise ground dedicated to Apollo Lykeios — hence the *Lyceum*. His followers became known as *Peripatetics*, probably from the ambulatory (*peripatos*) attached to the school grounds. The Lyceum pursued research across an extraordinary range: botany, biology, logic, mathematics, astronomy, physics, metaphysics, ethics, rhetoric, politics, and the arts, assembling in the process what ancient accounts describe as the first great library of antiquity. After Alexander's death in 323, anti-Macedonian feeling in Athens prompted Aristotle to withdraw to Chalcis on the island of Euboea, remarking — according to an oft-repeated ancient tale — that he saw no reason to permit Athens to sin twice against philosophy. He died there the following year, aged 63.\n\nOf roughly 200 works Aristotle is said to have written, only about 31 survive. None of them is a finished work in the literary sense: they read as teaching materials — notes compiled for the classroom rather than texts prepared for a wider readership.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nAristotle's most original contribution was the invention of formal logic. He showed that the validity of an argument depends on its *structure* rather than its content — as in the syllogism: all men are mortal; Socrates is a man; therefore Socrates is mortal — — a system so comprehensive that for roughly two thousand years it was taken to be the whole of logic, not merely its beginning.\n\nHe sharply departed from [[Plato]] by rejecting the Theory of Forms. Rather than positing a separate realm of eternal archetypes, Aristotle held that form is *immanent* in things: it does not exist independently of the particular substances it informs. His hylomorphism holds that every physical thing is a compound of matter (*hylê*) and form (*morphê*) — the bronze is the matter; the shape of the statue is the form.\n\nCentral to his natural philosophy are the four causes — material, formal, efficient, and final — which together constitute a complete explanation of any thing or event. The final cause, or *telos*, reflects his teleological view: things exhibit purposiveness, and are best explained in terms of the ends they serve. This runs through his biology, where he documented well over five hundred species in detail — observations not matched in scope or precision until the nineteenth century.\n\nIn ethics, Aristotle's central claim is that the highest good for a human being is *eudaimonia* — happiness or flourishing — achieved not by passive states but by activity: the active exercise of the soul in accordance with virtue. Virtues of character are acquired by habituation, and each is a mean between two extremes (courage lies between cowardice and rashness). His political philosophy extends this framework: the human being is by nature a *political animal*, and the *polis* exists not merely for survival but for living well.\n\n## Major Works\n\nAristotle's surviving works fall into three broad groups. The *Organon* — comprising the *Categories*, *On Interpretation*, *Prior Analytics*, *Posterior Analytics*, *Topics*, and *Sophistical Refutations* — is his logical corpus. His theoretical works include the *Physics*, *Metaphysics*, *On the Soul* (*De Anima*), *On the Heavens*, and the biological treatises (*History of Animals*, *Parts of Animals*, *Generation of Animals*). The practical works are the *Nicomachean Ethics* and the *Politics*. Rounding out the corpus are the *Rhetoric* and *Poetics* — the latter his celebrated but incomplete analysis of tragedy and the function of catharsis.\n\n## Quotes\n\nIt is evident that the city-state is a creation of nature, and that man is by nature a political animal.\n\n*— Politics, 1253a*\n\nThe weaker are always anxious for justice and equality. The strong pay no heed to either.\n\n*— Politics, 1318*\n\nMotion being eternal, the first mover, if there is but one, will be eternal also.\n\n*— Physics, 259a*",
