    "photo": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/6/6b/Diogenes-statue-Sinop-enhanced.jpg",
    "body": "Diogenes of Sinope (c. 404–323 BCE) was the most celebrated philosopher of the ancient Cynic school, notorious for reducing his own life to its barest essentials and using outrageous public behaviour to challenge Greek society's deepest assumptions. Where [[Socrates]] questioned comfortable beliefs through dialogue, Diogenes did so through the spectacle of his own life — earning the nickname \"the Dog\" and the description, attributed to [[Plato]], of \"a Socrates gone mad.\"\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nDiogenes was born in Sinope, a prosperous Greek trading city on the southern shore of the Black Sea. His father Hikesias was a banker in charge of the Sinopean mint. A scandal involving the defacing or re-stamping of currency — whether carried out by Diogenes himself, his father, or both — led to his exile from the city. He would later make something philosophically significant of the incident, describing his life's work as \"re-stamping\" not coins but human beings: putting false values out of circulation.\n\nHe made his way to Athens and, with notable persistence, attached himself to Antisthenes, a follower of [[Socrates]] known for his austere habits and reluctance to take on students. When Antisthenes threatened to drive him away with a stick, Diogenes reportedly replied that no stick would ever be strong enough to drive him from the teachings. From Antisthenes he took the seeds of what would become a radical philosophical program. He settled in Athens without permanent housing, famously taking up residence in a large ceramic storage jar (*pithos*) at the Metroön. He wore a single cloak that served as blanket and coat alike, carried a knapsack, and begged for food. One well-known story has him throwing away his wooden cup after watching a boy drink from his cupped hands, realising he already possessed everything he needed. \n\nAt some point Diogenes was captured by pirates while sailing and sold into slavery at Corinth. When asked at auction what he could do, he replied: \"Govern men.\" His buyer, Xeniades, placed him in charge of his sons' education — an arrangement that, whatever its historical accuracy, captures something essential about Diogenes: even as a slave, he considered himself the freer party. He spent his later years in or near Corinth, where his famous encounter with Alexander the Great reportedly took place. Alexander, having heard of Diogenes' reputation, came to offer him anything he wished. Diogenes, lying in the sun, asked only that Alexander step out of his light. Diogenes died around 323 BCE, probably in Corinth. None of the stories told about his death — voluntary suffocation, a meal of raw octopus, a dog bite — has the ring of historical record; the most plausible conclusion is that he died of old age in Corinth.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nThe cornerstone of Diogenes' philosophy was the distinction between *nature* and *convention*. Greek society, he argued, had buried genuine human needs under layers of artificial custom — wealth, ceremony, status, political allegiance. The task of the philosopher was to strip these away and live by nature and reason instead. This is what he meant by calling himself a citizen of the world rather than of any particular city: the *polis* was a human contrivance; the good life was not bounded by it.\n\nFrom this followed his principle of *shamelessness* (*anaideia*): if an action is not inherently wrong, performing it in public makes it no more wrong. This was not mere provocation. It rested on a consistent claim that conventions are arbitrary and that reason — not social pressure — should determine conduct. He observed that if you walk with your middle finger extended, people think you mad; extend the little finger and they think nothing of it. The madness, he suggested, lies in the convention, not the gesture. He insisted that \"for the conduct of life we need right reason or a halter\" — without reason, a person must simply be led about like an animal.\n\nA third pillar was *askēsis*, or rigorous self-training. Diogenes saw hardship not as deprivation but as a discipline that liberated a person from dependence on external goods. His austere lifestyle was intended to demonstrate that happiness and self-sufficiency were achievable without luxury, shelter, or status. He lit a lamp in broad daylight and walked around saying he was searching for a human being — meaning someone who actually lived by reason rather than merely conforming to appearances.\n\nDiogenes was also a sharp critic of [[Plato]]'s philosophy, treating abstract definition and metaphysical speculation with contempt. When [[Plato]] defined the human being as a \"featherless biped,\" Diogenes plucked a chicken and brought it into the lecture room: \"Here is Plato's human being.\" The story captures his method — not systematic argument, but action that exposes the absurdity lurking in over-refined theory.\n\n## Major Works\n\nIt is uncertain whether Diogenes left any writings at all. His biographer Diogenes Laertius cites the titles of thirteen dialogues and seven tragedies, including one apparently called *Pordalos* (*Fartery*) — which, if genuine, is consistent with his character. His *Republic* reportedly described an anarchist utopia in which people lived naturally, free from conventional family structure and political institutions. Letters attributed to him are widely considered later forgeries. Whatever he may have composed, nothing survives; what has come down to us is the legend of a life taken as the primary philosophical statement.\n\n## Quotes\n\nWhen Plato is asked what sort of man Diogenes is, he responds, \"A Socrates gone mad.\"\n\n*— Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Eminent Philosophers, 6.54*\n\nI had rather be mad than delighted.\n\n*— Attributed to Diogenes of Sinope*",
