    "body": "Plato (428/427–348/347 BCE) was an Athenian philosopher, student of [[Socrates]], teacher of [[Aristotle]], and founder of the Academy. By any reckoning he is one of the most influential writers in the history of Western thought.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nBorn to an aristocratic Athenian family — his father Ariston claimed descent from the god Poseidon, and his mother Perictione was related to the lawgiver Solon — Plato came of age during the political turbulence that followed Athens's defeat in the Peloponnesian War. His mother's relatives Critias and Charmides were among the Thirty Tyrants, the oligarchic clique installed by Sparta after their victory. As a young man, Plato entered the circle around [[Socrates]]. The trial and execution of [[Socrates]] in 399 BCE was decisive: it turned him away from the public life expected of his class and toward philosophy, and it provided the subject of some of his greatest writing.\n\nAfter [[Socrates]]'s death Plato travelled — probably to Megara, Egypt, and southern Italy, where he encountered followers of Pythagoras. He made three visits to Syracuse in Sicily, drawn by friendship with Dion, the brother-in-law of the tyrant Dionysius the Elder. Plato's attempt to put his ideal of the philosopher-king into practice — by educating Dionysius the Younger — came to nothing: the young tyrant proved unpersuadable, and in the ensuing instability Dion was murdered.\n\nBack in Athens, Plato founded the Academy in the 380s — an institution for philosophical and scientific inquiry that drew outstanding mathematicians such as Theaetetus and Eudoxus of Cnidus, and where [[Aristotle]] spent twenty years. It is often cited as the ancestor of the modern university and outlasted Plato by centuries.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nPlato's most distinctive contribution is the Theory of Forms. In his view, the particular things we perceive — beautiful objects, just acts, equal lengths — are imperfect, temporary versions of eternal, unchanging archetypes that only reason can grasp. These Forms — Justice, Beauty, Equality, and above all the Good — constitute the deepest level of reality; the visible world possesses whatever order and meaning it has only because it approximates them. This split between the visible and the intelligible runs through his metaphysics, his epistemology (genuine knowledge is knowledge of Forms, not particular things), and his ethics.\n\nIn ethics and moral psychology, Plato departed from [[Socrates]]'s purely intellectualist view. Living well, he argued, demands not just correct understanding but a properly trained emotional life — the three parts of the soul (reason, spirit, and appetite) must work in concert rather than at cross-purposes. His greatest work, the *Republic*, extends this analysis to the state: a just city is one in which reason, represented by philosopher-kings, governs. The Allegory of the Cave — in which prisoners mistake shadows on a wall for reality — dramatises the philosopher's task of turning from illusion toward genuine understanding. Plato wrote with great literary skill, favouring the dialogue form; his works remain among the most readable in the philosophical tradition.\n\n## Major Works\n\nPlato's works are traditionally divided into three periods. The early, *Socratic* dialogues — including the *Apology*, *Euthyphro*, *Crito*, *Laches*, *Meno*, *Protagoras*, and *Gorgias* — explore ethical questions in the spirit of the historical [[Socrates]], without advancing positive doctrines. The middle dialogues — the *Republic*, *Phaedo*, *Symposium*, and *Phaedrus* — are his literary and philosophical masterpieces, presenting the Theory of Forms and his mature views on the soul, love, and justice. The late dialogues — *Parmenides*, *Theaetetus*, *Sophist*, *Statesman*, *Timaeus*, *Philebus*, and *Laws* — are more technical and in some cases revisionary, subjecting earlier positions to rigorous scrutiny. At least 25 dialogues are considered authentic, with several others of disputed authorship.\n\n## Quotes\n\nPhilosophy begins in wonder.\n\n*— Theaetetus, 155d*\n\nThe true lover of knowledge naturally strives for truth, and is not content with common opinion, but soars with undimmed and unwearied passion till he grasps the essential nature of things.\n\n*— The Republic, 490a*\n\nDemocracy . . . is a charming form of government, full of variety and disorder, and dispensing a sort of equality to equals and unequals alike.\n\n*— The Republic, 558c*",
