    "body": "Socrates (469–399 BCE) was an Athenian philosopher who wrote nothing but is considered one of the founders of Western philosophy. His trial and death at the hands of Athenian democracy has become the founding myth of the discipline.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nBorn in Athens to Sophroniscus, a stonemason, and Phaenarete, a midwife, Socrates came from a modest background with no claim to noble birth. He received an education in reading, writing, poetry, music, and athletics, but rather than practising a trade he spent his days in the agora, the Athenian marketplace, questioning anyone willing to speak with him — merchants, statesmen, and sophists alike. He acquired a following of wealthy young men, among them [[Plato]].\n\nBy the standards of his culture Socrates cut an extraordinary figure. He was famously ugly — bulging eyes, a snub nose, large lips, a potbelly — and paid little attention to his appearance, wearing the same clothes day and night. He fought as a soldier with real distinction: at Potidaea in 432 BCE he pulled Alcibiades out of danger during the fighting; he also fought at Delium and Amphipolis. He was married to Xanthippe and had three sons.\n\nHis political associations made him suspect. Close associates including Critias and Charmides led the Thirty Tyrants installed by Sparta after Athens's defeat in the Peloponnesian War. Yet when the Thirty ordered him to help arrest a democratic general, Socrates refused. The political atmosphere after democracy was restored was charged, and in 399 BCE he was tried on charges of impiety — specifically, introducing new divinities, including a private inner voice he called his *daimon* — and of corrupting the youth. Convicted by a jury of around five hundred citizens, he was sentenced to death by hemlock. He refused an opportunity to escape and met his death calmly; [[Plato]]'s *Phaedo* records the scene.\n\nA note on sources: Socrates wrote nothing himself. Our knowledge of his thought comes principally through [[Plato]]'s dialogues, supplemented by Xenophon and the comic playwright Aristophanes. Scholars have long debated how to separate the historical Socrates from the literary character — a question sometimes called the Socratic problem — and it has no settled answer.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nSocrates's starting point was a radical claim about ignorance. When the oracle at Delphi declared that no one was wiser than Socrates, he understood this to mean not that he possessed superior knowledge, but that he alone was aware of his own ignorance — whereas others mistook ignorance for knowledge. This \"Socratic ignorance\" was the precondition for honest inquiry, not a counsel of despair.\n\nHis method — the *elenchus*, or Socratic method — proceeds by question and answer, pressing an interlocutor to define their terms and exposing contradictions in their answers. Socrates described this not as teaching but as midwifery: helping others give birth to ideas already latent in them. The goal was genuine understanding or, failing that, honest *aporia* — the acknowledgment that one does not know.\n\nBeyond method, Socrates held substantive ethical positions. Virtue, he argued, is a form of knowledge: those who do wrong do so from ignorance, not wickedness — no one errs willingly. He held that it is better to suffer injustice than to commit it, and that the care of one's soul — its moral and intellectual condition — matters far more than wealth, reputation, or bodily comfort. His life's work found its summary statement in a single sentence: the unexamined life is not worth living.\n\n## Major Works\n\nSocrates wrote nothing. Our knowledge of his thought rests on texts by others, principally [[Plato]], whose early dialogues are the most philosophically detailed and reliable source. The most important of these are the *Apology* (Socrates's defence speech at his trial), the *Crito* (on the obligation to obey the law), and the *Phaedo* (on the soul and Socrates's final hours). The *Symposium* contains the celebrated account of love as a longing for the Form of Beauty; the *Republic* presents Socratic questioning in the context of a larger argument about justice. Xenophon's *Memorabilia* and *Apology* offer a complementary — and rather different — portrait. Aristophanes's comedy *Clouds* (423 BCE), though a caricature, is the earliest surviving depiction of Socrates and is referenced by [[Plato]]'s Socrates himself at his trial.\n\n## Quotes\n\nThe unexamined life is not worth living.\n\n*— Socrates*",
