    "body": "Pyrrho of Elis (c. 360–c. 270 BCE) was the Greek philosopher from whom the sceptical tradition of Pyrrhonism takes its name, and he is usually counted as the first sceptic in Greek philosophy. He wrote nothing and built no formal school, yet the example of his unshakeable calm, together with a few reports of his teaching, inspired a movement that flourished for centuries after his death.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nPyrrho came from Elis, a city in the Peloponnese near the Ionian Sea. According to Diogenes Laertius — the source of most surviving anecdotes about him — his father was named Pleistarchus, and he worked as a painter before philosophy drew him away from it. He attached himself to Anaxarchus of Abdera, a thinker in the line of Democritus and most likely his teacher, and the two are said to have left Greece with the army of Alexander the Great. The expedition carried Pyrrho as far as India, where he reportedly met the \"naked wise men\" (gymnosophists) and the Magi of Persia. Laertius claims this meeting gave rise to his philosophy, though it is unclear what the claim rests on, and modern scholars doubt how far any Indian thinker could have shaped him.\n\nBack in Greece he taught a way of life that won him several followers, the most important being Timon of Phlius. At home he enjoyed genuine fame: Pausanias, who wrote a guidebook to Greece, records a statue of him in the Elean marketplace, and Laertius adds that his townsmen made him a high priest and freed all philosophers from taxation in his honour. He may have belonged to the Klytidiai, a clan of local seers. Though his family had money, he lived plainly and mostly alone, and is said to have had a sister keeping house comfortably nearby. He died at Elis at around the age of ninety.\n\nMuch of what we hear concerns his bearing rather than his arguments. The stories present a man of extraordinary composure who kept his calm whatever befell him, even under the knife of ancient surgery or aboard a ship in a storm. He cared little for convention, doing menial work others of his standing would leave to servants, and on one occasion washing a pig. Some reports were plainly hostile: one has him so mistrustful of his senses that he ignored cliffs and oncoming carts and had to be steered from harm by friends. But the consistent impression is of a tranquillity that set him apart.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nSince Pyrrho left no writings, his thought has to be reconstructed from later reports, most of them traceable to Timon. The central piece of evidence is the so-called Aristocles passage, a summary by Aristocles of Messene of an account by Timon, preserved by the Christian writer Eusebius. It organises Pyrrho's philosophy around three questions: what are things like by nature, how should we be disposed toward them, and what results for the person who takes up that disposition?\n\nThe first answer is that things are by nature undifferentiated, unstable, and indeterminable, so that our senses and opinions neither tell the truth nor lie. We should therefore hold no opinions and favour no side, ready to say of anything that it no more is than is not. The payoff arrives in two stages — first speechlessness (*aphasia*), then *ataraxia*, the freedom from disturbance that was the point of the whole exercise.\n\nWhat this amounts to has been argued over ever since. On one reading Pyrrho makes a claim about reality itself, that things genuinely have no fixed nature; on another, a claim about us, that we are in no position to determine how things stand. The distinction matters, because only the second makes him a true forerunner of the later sceptics, who took care never to pronounce on the hidden nature of things. A separate report in Diogenes Laertius has him deny that anything is by nature fine or shameful, just or unjust, holding instead that people act by custom and habit — which suggests his doubts may have centred on judgements of value.\n\nIf one withholds judgement like this, how does one act at all? The answer credited to the early Pyrrhonists is that one goes by appearances, by how things seem, without treating them as a guide to how things really are. This let Pyrrho distrust his senses in principle while still living an ordinary life, and it explains his calm: a person who holds no firm view about what is worth pursuing or avoiding has far less to be troubled by than the rest of us.\n\n## Major Works\n\nPyrrho wrote nothing, apart from a poem said to date from Alexander's campaign, which did not survive. Everything known about him reaches us secondhand. His pupil Timon of Phlius cast his outlook into verse and prose, among them the *Silloi* (*Lampoons*), satirical sketches ridiculing rival philosophers; only fragments are left. Generations later Aenesidemus revived the tradition, and it received its fullest surviving expression in the *Outlines of Pyrrhonism* by Sextus Empiricus, composed some four hundred years after Pyrrho's death. Through these later hands — Timon, Aristocles, Diogenes Laertius, and Sextus — a man who published nothing came to give his name to one of the two great sceptical traditions of the ancient world.\n\n## Quotes\n\nHe denied that anything was honourable or dishonourable, just or unjust. And so, universally, he held that there is nothing really existent, but custom and convention govern human action; for no single thing is in itself any more this than that.\n\n*— Diogenes Laertius, Lives of the Eminent Philosophers, 9.61*",
