    "body": "Epicurus (341–270 BCE) was a Greek philosopher who founded a school in Athens that survived as a living community for centuries after his death. Building on the atomist tradition of Democritus, he constructed an integrated system—physics, ethics, and theology working together—whose purpose was to free people from the fears that make life miserable.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nEpicurus was born in 341 BCE on the island of Samos, where his Athenian parents had settled as part of a colony. His father Neocles was a schoolteacher, his mother Chairestrate; both were from the deme Gargettus. He came to philosophy at fourteen—reportedly after being unable to get his teacher to explain what chaos meant in the poetry of Hesiod. His first philosophical guide was a Platonist named Pamphilus; far more consequential were three years studying under Nausiphanes—who taught in the tradition of Democritus—at Teos on the Ionian coast. The atomist tradition he absorbed there shaped everything that followed.\n\nAt eighteen, Epicurus went to Athens to complete two years of military training required for Athenian citizenship. When Athens subsequently lost Samos after the Lamian War, he joined his family in Colophon on the coast of Asia Minor, spending the next decade working out his philosophical outlook. He began teaching at thirty-two, first in Mytilene on the island of Lesbos and then in Lampsacus on the mainland—gathering around him the companions who would eventually follow him to Athens.\n\nIn 306 BCE Epicurus purchased a house and garden in Athens, which became the seat of his school—the Garden, or *Ho Kepos*. It opened its doors to women and at least one of Epicurus's own slaves. Life was genuinely simple: barley bread and water, with a small daily wine allowance; during a famine, Epicurus sustained the school by dividing what food remained into small daily portions. Members owned their possessions individually, and the community was held together by friendship rather than institutional structure.\n\nHe died in 270 BCE, around the age of seventy, in considerable pain. In a letter dictated to his friend Idomeneus on his final day he expressed affection and contentment, noting that the pleasures of his mind outweighed what his body was enduring. His will freed his slaves, made provision for the children of friends, and arranged for his birthday to be celebrated annually.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nEpicurus was unusual among ancient philosophers in insisting that physics, ethics, and theology had to be studied together—each did essential work in the same therapeutic project: freeing people from the fears that produce unnecessary suffering.\n\nHis physics built on Democritus's atomism but modified it in important ways. All physical reality consists of atoms—solid, indivisible particles—moving through empty space. Epicurus added weight as an intrinsic atomic property and introduced the *swerve*: a minute, unpredictable deviation in an atom's path, needed both to explain how atoms ever collide and to preserve space for human freedom within an otherwise deterministic universe. The soul, on this account, is itself material—fine atoms distributed through the body—and disperses completely at death.\n\nThis had direct ethical consequences. If the soul dissolves at death, there is no afterlife and no punishment to dread. Epicurus pressed this into a careful argument: the living haven't yet encountered death, while the dead no longer have any experience at all—there is no subject left for death to harm. So death is, as he put it, \"nothing to us.\" The gods exist, but they live in the spaces between worlds, undisturbed and indifferent to human affairs. No divine wrath awaits anyone.\n\nWith these two fears dismantled, Epicurus could turn to what happiness actually requires. He identified it with pleasure, but meant something specific: *ataraxia*, a stable tranquility of mind combined with freedom from physical pain—not intense gratification. He drew a distinction between kinetic pleasures (the enjoyment of satisfying a desire as it is being fulfilled) and static pleasures (the settled condition once desire is met). The static pleasures are superior because they involve no craving. This led him to classify desires into three types: natural and necessary desires—for food, shelter, warmth—are easily satisfied and worth meeting; natural but non-necessary desires, for delicacies and luxuries, create needless dependence; vain desires for wealth, power, or fame have no natural stopping point, and so perpetually generate new wanting rather than satisfaction.\n\nFriendship runs through all of this. Epicurus wrote of friendship dancing around the world and bidding us wake to happiness—an image of unusual warmth from a philosopher so associated with restraint. The Garden was itself an experiment in what a community built around friendship could be: mutual care that provided a form of security philosophy alone could not.\n\n## Major Works\n\nOf Epicurus's reportedly vast output, almost nothing remains. Three letters preserved by the biographer Diogenes Laërtius give the clearest picture of his thought: the *Letter to Herodotus* (on physics), the *Letter to Pythocles* (on meteorological phenomena), and the *Letter to Menoeceus* (on ethics). Diogenes also preserved the *Kyriai Doxai* (*Principal Doctrines*)—forty short ethical aphorisms. Fragments of his major theoretical work, *Peri Physeōs* (*On Nature*), originally compiled in thirty-seven books, have been recovered from papyri excavated at Herculaneum. For the broader reach of his ideas, Lucretius's *De Rerum Natura* (*On the Nature of Things*)—a six-book Latin poem written in the first century BCE—remains the most complete surviving account of the Epicurean system.\n\n## Quotes\n\nWe must not make a pretence of doing philosophy, but really do it; for what we need is not the semblance of health but real health.\n\n*— Quoted in A. A. Long, Hellenistic Philosophy, 62*\n\nWe begin every act of choice and avoidance from pleasure, and it is to pleasure that we return using our experience of pleasure as the criterion of every good thing.\n\n*— Letter to Menoeceus, Hellenistic Philosophy, p. 62*",
