    "body": "Zeno of Citium (c. 334–262 BCE) was a Greek philosopher from Cyprus who founded Stoicism, the school that became the most influential philosophy of the Hellenistic age and remained a major force through the Roman era. He taught that the good life lies in living according to nature and reason, and out of the moral teachings of the Cynics he built a single system spanning logic, physics, and ethics.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nZeno was born in Citium, a city on Cyprus inhabited by both Greeks and Phoenicians. His father, Mnaseas, was a merchant; his mother's name was not recorded. His ancestry has been disputed — variously called Greek, Phoenician, or a mixture of the two — and contemporaries sometimes referred to him as \"the Phoenician.\"\n\nMost of what is known about his life comes from the anecdotes preserved by Diogenes Laërtius. By one account Zeno came to philosophy through misadventure: shipwrecked on a voyage around the age of twenty-two, he made his way to Athens, and in a bookshop happened upon Xenophon's *Memorabilia*. He was so taken with its portrait of [[Socrates]] that he asked where men of that kind might be found. The Cynic Crates of Thebes was passing by, and the bookseller pointed to him; Zeno became his pupil. He is said to have remarked afterward that he \"made a prosperous voyage\" when he was shipwrecked.\n\nBesides Crates, Zeno studied with teachers of the Megarian school, among them Stilpo and the dialecticians Diodorus Cronus and Philo, and studied Platonist philosophy under Xenocrates and Polemo. Around 300 BCE he began teaching in the *Stoa Poikile*, the painted colonnade in the Athenian agora that gave his followers their name: at first called \"Zenonians,\" they came to be known as \"Stoics,\" after the porch where he lectured.\n\nDespite his foreign birth Zeno became a respected figure in Athens, keeping the plain, ascetic habits he had absorbed from the Cynics and a reputation for a severe, earnest temperament. He declined an offer of Athenian citizenship, not wishing to seem disloyal to Citium. King Antigonus II Gonatas of Macedonia admired him, and when Zeno would not come to his court he sent his pupil Persaeus in his place. Among his other students were Aristo of Chios, Sphaerus, and Cleanthes, who succeeded him as head of the school.\n\nHe died around 262 BCE, reportedly aged seventy-two. The story told by Diogenes Laërtius is that, on leaving the school one day, he tripped and broke a toe; reading the fall as a summons, he quoted a line of poetry — \"I come, I come, why dost thou call for me?\" — and ended his own life. Athens gave him a public tomb and a decree praising him as a man who had lived the virtue he taught.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nZeno divided philosophy into three parts — logic, physics, and ethics — and, more than his contemporaries, insisted on treating them as a single connected whole rather than giving priority to any one.\n\nOn knowledge, he taught that certainty is reached by stages, which he liked to demonstrate with his hand. The open palm was perception; the fingers drawn in, assent; the closed fist, comprehension, which he named *katalepsis*; and the fist gripped tight by the other hand, knowledge — a state, he said, that only the wise attain. On his account the mind can grant or withhold its assent to the impressions it receives.\n\nHis physics identified the universe with God: a single rational, living whole. Following Heraclitus, he described nature as an \"artistically working fire\" that runs through all things and shapes them by design, so that the order of the world is at once providence and fate. Individual souls are portions of this same world-fire, and the cosmos passes through recurring cycles of formation and destruction.\n\nHis ethics supplied Stoicism with its lasting formula: the end of life is to live in agreement with nature, which for a rational creature means living by reason. The sole good is virtue and the sole evil is vice; happiness is \"a good flow of life,\" reached when one's own reason runs in harmony with the universal reason, or *Logos*, that governs everything. A bad feeling (*pathos*) he defined as a movement of the mind against nature and reason. Here he parted from the Cynics: where they dismissed everything but virtue as worthless, Zeno allowed that \"indifferent\" things such as health could still carry value and be reasonably preferred, and he coined the term *kathēkon*, the \"fitting action,\" for conduct suited to one's nature.\n\n## Major Works\n\nNone of Zeno's writings survive except as quotations in later authors. The most famous, and most notorious, was his *Republic* (*Politeia*), composed early under Cynic influence as a counterpart to — or attack on — [[Plato]]'s book of the same title. It sketched an ideal community of the wise with no temples, law courts, money, or conventional institutions. Diogenes Laërtius records the titles of some two dozen further treatises, among them *On Life according to Nature*, *On Passions*, *On Duty*, *On Law*, and *On Greek Education*, covering the logical, physical, and ethical sides of his teaching. What Zeno left unfinished — his logic in particular — was developed and systematised by later Stoics, above all Chrysippus.\n\n## Quotes\n\nWe have two ears and one mouth, so we should listen more than we say.\n\n*— As reported in Diogenes Laertius, Lives of Eminent Philosophers, 7.23*",
