    "body": "Marcus Tullius Cicero (106–43 BCE) was a Roman orator, lawyer, politician, and philosopher whose life ran alongside the collapse of the Roman Republic. He set out to make Greek philosophy speak Latin, and his summaries of the Hellenistic schools — among them the heirs of [[Plato]], [[Aristotle]], [[Epicurus]], and [[Zeno of Citium]] — remain a chief source of what we know about them. He always put politics first, valuing philosophy most of all as a means to effective public action.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nCicero was born on 3 January 106 BCE into an aristocratic family of equestrian rank that lacked both great wealth and a pedigree among the small circle of households that monopolized high office. Lacking that pedigree, he made his career in the law rather than the army, for he hated war, and trained in jurisprudence, rhetoric, and philosophy. A gifted advocate, he was elected to each of the major Roman offices — quaestor, aedile, praetor, and consul — at the first attempt and the youngest age allowed, which made him a senator.\n\nAs consul in 63 BCE he uncovered the conspiracy of Catiline, which aimed to seize the state by force, and had five of the plotters executed without trial — an act he boasted had saved the commonwealth, and one his opponents never forgave. When Caesar, Pompey, and Crassus took control of Roman politics in 60 BCE, Cicero refused to join them and stayed loyal to the Senate; in 58 the tribune Clodius passed a law condemning anyone who had killed a citizen without trial, and Cicero fled into exile with his property seized. Shut out of politics, he used the time for his first concentrated bout of philosophy, and was recalled about eighteen months later.\n\nIn the civil war of 49 BCE he sided half-heartedly with Pompey, sure that whichever of Pompey or Caesar won, the Republic was finished either way. Caesar won, pardoned him, and let him return in 47 but barred him from politics, so he turned back to writing. After Caesar's murder on the Ides of March in 44, Cicero made one last bid to save the Republic, attacking Mark Antony in the speeches known as the Philippics. It cost him his life: when Antony, Lepidus, and Octavian divided power, each named the enemies he wanted dead, and Antony put Cicero on the list while Octavian, who owed him much, did not intervene. He was killed on 7 December 43 BCE, and Antony had his head and hands nailed up on the Senate's speakers' platform.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nCicero put philosophy in the service of politics, and the service he had in mind was the rescue of the Republic. Its troubles, he thought, sprang from a loss of virtue among Rome's leaders, who chased fame, wealth, and power instead of older Roman virtue; were the elite to reform themselves and hold others to the same standard by law, the Republic might revive.\n\nTo make philosophy useful he first had to make it Roman. He translated Greek works into Latin and coined Latin terms where none would serve, giving later tongues the words behind the English *morals*, *property*, *individual*, *science*, *image*, and *appetite*.\n\nAll his life he professed allegiance to the Academy and its scepticism — the conviction that certainty is beyond us, so that the most one can do is judge a position more or less plausible, and that judgement too stays open to a stronger argument. The stance suited a lawyer and politician, who must weigh every side of a case, and it explains his fondness for the dialogue, which let him set out rival arguments without committing himself to any. But he would not carry scepticism into ethics and politics, where doubt struck him as dangerous; there he leaned on the Stoics. From them he took the idea of a natural law grounded in reason and shared by gods and men, the source of all just human law, and the duty this lays on us to take part in the life of our communities. Justice, on this view, is to be pursued for its own sake and not merely from fear of punishment.\n\n## Major Works\n\nCicero's writing falls into three kinds: his philosophical works, about sixty surviving speeches, and some nine hundred letters full of the everyday bargaining of Roman politics. His philosophy came in two bursts; the first, in the 50s, produced *On the Orator*, *On the Republic*, and *On the Laws*. *On the Republic*, which survives only in fragments — some recovered in the Vatican in 1820 — describes the ideal state as a mixed constitution blending monarchy, aristocracy, and democracy, and closes with the famous Dream of Scipio; *On the Laws* sets out the laws such a state would keep. The greater part came in 45 and 44 BCE, after his daughter Tullia's death and under Caesar's dictatorship: among these are *On Ends*, on the highest good; the *Tusculan Disputations*; *On the Nature of the Gods*; and *On Duties*, addressed to his son Marcus and often the best way into his thought. Several works are lost, including the *Hortensius*, an exhortation to philosophy that later turned the young Augustine toward it.\n\n## Quotes\n\nTo be ignorant of what occurred before you were born is to remain always a child. For what is the worth of human life, unless it is woven into the life of our ancestors by the records of history?\n\n*— De Oratore, 34.120*\n\nThere is nothing so absurd but some philosopher has said it.\n\n*— De Divinatione, II, 58*\n\nThe good of the people is the chief law.\n\n*— De Legibus, III, 3.8*",
