    "body": "Lucius Annaeus Seneca (c. 4 BCE - 65 CE) was a Roman Stoic philosopher, playwright, and statesman who tutored and advised the emperor Nero. Writing in Latin rather than Greek, he became one of the most widely read sources for Stoic thought, and his writings shaped how later readers, from early Christian thinkers to Descartes, understood what it meant to live philosophically.\n\n## Biographical Details\n\nSeneca was born into a provincial noble family in Corduba, Spain. His father, Seneca the Elder, taught rhetoric in Rome, while his mother Helvia raised him at the family estate. Two brothers survived alongside him: Gallio, who later met the apostle Paul while posted to Achaea, and Marcus Annaeus Mela, whose son Lucan became a noted poet. An aunt brought him to Rome to complete his education, where he studied oratory and took up philosophy under the Sextii, a school blending Stoicism with ascetic Neo-Pythagoreanism. Illness later sent him to convalesce in Egypt.\n\nBy around 31 CE he was back in Rome, pursuing law and politics; he narrowly escaped execution under Caligula. Claudius banished him to Corsica in 41 CE after convicting him of adultery with Julia Livilla, the emperor's niece; there he studied and wrote his three consolation essays. Agrippina the Younger, married to Claudius, engineered his return to Rome in 49 and set him up as tutor to her son Nero. He was made praetor in 50, married the wealthy Pompeia Paulina, and allied himself with Sextus Afranius Burrus, commander of the Praetorian Guard.\n\nAfter Claudius died in 54, Seneca and Burrus ruled through Nero, writing his speeches and pushing through fiscal and legal reforms that softened Roman treatment of the enslaved. But favor with a tyrant came at a price: in 59 both men were complicit, one way or another, in Nero's murder of his own mother, Agrippina. Burrus's death in 62 prompted Seneca to retire from politics and devote his final years to writing. In 65, accused of involvement in the Pisonian plot to kill Nero, he was ordered to take his own life. He first opened the veins in his wrists and legs, but blood loss was slow given his frailty; a dose of hemlock had no better effect, since his circulation was too poor to carry it; only immersion in a hot bath, and its steam, finally killed him. Per his own instructions, he was cremated without ceremony. Ancient sources depict his final hours as composed, with a last meal among friends, recalling the death of Socrates.\n\n## Key Ideas\n\nSeneca called himself a Stoic but treated the school's founders as guides rather than masters, willing to draw on Epicurean or Platonic arguments he judged true, and thought directly in Latin rather than translating Greek terminology.\n\nMuch of his writing addresses the passions, above all anger, fear, and grief. On the Stoic account, an emotion is not an irrational force fighting reason but a mistaken judgment: the belief that some external event is genuinely good or bad. In *On Anger*, Seneca distinguishes an involuntary first reaction, a flinch or a jolt, from anger itself, which arises only once the mind assents to the judgment that a wrong deserves resentment. Because that assent is within a person's control, so is the anger that follows, and he treats keeping anger within reasonable bounds as incoherent, a contradiction in terms.\n\nSeneca also gave a practical edge to the Stoic claim that virtue alone is good. Health, wealth, and reputation carry real value and are worth pursuing sensibly, but contribute nothing to happiness, which depends entirely on the soundness of one's judgment. He favored concrete cases over abstract argument, a plain meal, an unfashionable haircut, to show how easily people mistake mere conveniences for goods.\n\nHe returned often to how a life should be divided between public office and philosophical study. Seneca argued that we belong to two communities at once: the immediate one of family, city, and political office, and the boundless one of humanity as a whole, which philosophical writing serves just as directly as statesmanship serves the first. This conviction runs through his treatise *On Benefits*, on what it takes to give and receive help well.\n\n## Major Works\n\nSeneca's best-known writings are the *Letters to Lucilius*, 124 essays addressed to a friend, ranging from daily concerns to sustained Stoic doctrine. Most of his other philosophical prose survives under the general title *Dialogues*, including three consolations: to his mother Helvia, written during his own exile, and to Marcia and Polybius, each mourning a lost son, along with *On Anger*, *On Tranquility of Mind*, and *On the Shortness of Life*. *On Mercy*, ostensibly written for Nero, argues that restraint in the use of power is a ruler's greatest virtue, and *On Benefits* examines the exchange of favors between givers and recipients. His *Natural Questions* surveys meteorological phenomena as a route to understanding the cosmos and easing the fear of death. Seneca also wrote eight surviving tragedies, among them *Medea*, *Phaedra*, and *Thyestes*, and a satirical skit on Claudius's deification, the *Apocolocyntosis*, or \"Pumpkinification.\"\n\n## Quotes\n\nThere are more things, Lucilius, that frighten us than injure us, and we suffer more in imagination than in reality.\n\n*— Epistulae ad Lucilium*\n\nThe pain of a disappointed wish necessarily produces less effect upon the mind if a man has not certainly promised himself success.\n\n*— De Tranquillitate Animi*\n\nMan is a social animal.\n\n*— De Beneficiis*",
